# Ethernet to Internet Sharing using NetworkManager + IPTables

This guide configures `eth0` as a local LAN interface (`192.168.0.1/24`) and shares Internet access from another interface (`wwan0`, `usb0`, or `wlan0`) using IP forwarding and NAT.

---

## 1. Configure eth0 with Static IP

Check available connections:

```bash
nmcli connection show
```

Set `eth0` to `192.168.0.1/24`:

```bash
sudo nmcli connection modify "Wired connection 1" ipv4.addresses 192.168.0.1/24
sudo nmcli connection modify "Wired connection 1" ipv4.method manual
sudo nmcli connection up "Wired connection 1"
```

Verify:

```bash
nmcli connection show
ip addr show eth0
```

---

## 2. Enable IP Forwarding

Edit sysctl configuration:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/sysctl.conf
```

Add or uncomment:

```text
net.ipv4.ip_forward=1
```

Apply changes:

```bash
sudo sysctl -p
```

Verify:

```bash
cat /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward
```

Expected output:

```text
1
```

---

## 3. Install Persistent IPTables Rules

Update packages:

```bash
sudo apt update
```

Install:

```bash
sudo apt install iptables-persistent
```

Verify:

```bash
dpkg -l | grep iptables-persistent
```

---

## 4. Clear Existing Rules (Optional)

Flush NAT and forwarding rules:

```bash
sudo iptables -t nat -F
sudo iptables -F FORWARD
```

Verify:

```bash
sudo iptables -t nat -L -n -v
sudo iptables -L FORWARD -n -v
```

---

## 5. Configure NAT and Forwarding

### Option A: Share Internet from WWAN (4G/5G Modem)

```bash
sudo iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o wwan0 -j MASQUERADE

sudo iptables -A FORWARD -i eth0 -o wwan0 -j ACCEPT

sudo iptables -A FORWARD -i wwan0 -o eth0 \
  -m state --state RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT
```

---

### Option B: Share Internet from USB Network Interface

```bash
sudo iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o usb0 -j MASQUERADE

sudo iptables -A FORWARD -i eth0 -o usb0 -j ACCEPT

sudo iptables -A FORWARD -i usb0 -o eth0 \
  -m state --state RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT
```

---

### Option C: Share Internet from Wi-Fi

```bash
sudo iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o wlan0 -j MASQUERADE

sudo iptables -A FORWARD -i eth0 -o wlan0 -j ACCEPT

sudo iptables -A FORWARD -i wlan0 -o eth0 \
  -m state --state RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT
```

---

## 6. Save Rules Permanently

Save current IPTables configuration:

```bash
sudo netfilter-persistent save
```

Reload saved rules:

```bash
sudo netfilter-persistent reload
```

---

## 7. Verify Configuration

Check NAT rules:

```bash
sudo iptables -t nat -L -n -v
```

Check forwarding rules:

```bash
sudo iptables -L FORWARD -n -v
```

Check IP forwarding:

```bash
cat /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward
```

---

## Network Topology

```text
                Internet
                    |
         +----------+----------+
         |                     |
       wwan0 / usb0 / wlan0
                    |
             Linux Gateway
             eth0: 192.168.0.1
                    |
            Ethernet Clients
       (192.168.0.x network)
```

---

## Notes

* `eth0` acts as the LAN interface.
* `wwan0`, `usb0`, or `wlan0` acts as the WAN (Internet) interface.
* IP forwarding must be enabled for routing to work.
* NAT (MASQUERADE) allows multiple LAN devices to share a single Internet connection.
* Rules saved using `netfilter-persistent` survive reboots.

